It's only Tuesday and if you thought the day couldn't get any worse, we have some bad news for you. Today is the longest day of the year!

On Tuesday, June 21st, we will witness the summer solstice or the June solstice, i.e. the longest day of the year in the Northern Hemisphere and the shortest day in the Southern Hemisphere. This happens when the Earth’s north pole has its maximum tilt towards the sun. June solstice also marks the onset of the summer season in the Northern Hemisphere and winter season in the Southern Hemisphere.

So why don’t you make the longest day of the year longer by explaining to your friends why it’s the longest day of the year.

Karnataka’s beer industry is facing a sobering reality. Beer sales dipped by over 18% in the first half of 2025 compared to the same period last year, according to data from the excise department. Just 209.9 lakh cartons were sold between January and June, down from 257 lakh in H1 2024, with January alone seeing a steep 30.6% crash. Even peak summer months like April and May didn’t help, recording drops of 16% and 26% respectively.

Interestingly, revenue actually inched up by 0.6%, pointing to a rise in prices — something that’s been hurting the industry more than helping. Industry players blame frequent tax hikes, rising retail costs, and uncertainty in excise policy. A pub owner from Church Street said, “We can’t even increase food prices anymore, people just stop showing up.” In smaller towns like Shivamogga, shopkeepers say regular customers now buy one bottle instead of four.

In response, the Karnataka government has recently tweaked the Additional Excise Duty (AED) structure. The old system of 195% AED plus ₹130 per bulk litre has now been replaced with a flat 200% AED, which officials say will reduce the burden on low-end beer. But since this has only been in effect for a month, it’s too early to tell if it’ll pour relief back into the market.

Adding to the slowdown is the early onset of monsoon, which dulled the summer beer rush — usually the best time for sales in Bengaluru and beyond. Excise commissioner Venkatesh Kumar R said, “April to July is peak beer season, but this year’s rain threw off the rhythm.”

Whether the new duty structure will revive the party remains to be seen — for now, Karnataka’s beer market seems to be on ice.
